e past an economic cause for a contextual, historical force. Tracing “incentive” from its roots in antiquity to its uptake by neoclassical and then Chicago-school economists, Robert O. McDonald diagnoses the spread of incentives across the social, cultural, and political field and warns readers of the dangers of handing over causality to the economists.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Mrz 2024) 0aEconomicsxPsychological aspects. 0aIncentive (Psychology). 4aBusiness and Economics : Economic History. 4aCommunication : Communication. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aPsychology : Psychoanalysis. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2023z978311149193640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143849410440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438494104423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438494104/original  a978-3-11-149193-6  SUNY Press eBook Package 2023b2023  aGBV-deGruyter-alles